---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import OpportunityCard from '@/components/OpportunityCard.astro';

const BASE = '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08';

import imgTpwTierComparison from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-tier-comparison-detail.png';
import imgTpwSizeSelector from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-size-selector-detail.png';
import imgTpwReviewsBreakdown from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-reviews-breakdown-detail.png';
import imgTpwFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/tpw-full-desktop.png';
import imgOnAtf from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-atf-detail.png';
import imgOnReviews from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-reviews-section.png';
import imgOnFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/on-full-desktop.png';
import imgHealfSubscribe from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-subscribe-cta-detail.png';
import imgHealfFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-full-desktop.png';
import imgHealfLower from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/healf-lower-desktop.png';
import imgHuelAtf from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/huel-atf-detail.png';
import imgHuelFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/huel-full-desktop.png';
import imgBulkMid from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/bulk-mid-desktop.png';
import imgBulkLower from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/bulk-lower-desktop.png';
import imgBulkFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/bulk-full-desktop.png';
import imgNakedRecommend from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/naked-nutrition-recommend-metric-detail.png';
import imgNakedReviewVariant from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/naked-nutrition-review-variant-detail.png';
import imgNakedFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/naked-nutrition-full-desktop.png';
import imgMpFull from '@/assets/reports/competitors/pdp-competitor-analysis-2026-06-08/myprotein-full-desktop.png';
---

<ReportLayout title="PDP Competitor Analysis — June 2026">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">PDP Competitor Analysis</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Product Detail Page &mdash; Analysed 8 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Six competitor PDPs were reviewed against Myprotein's Impact Whey Protein page:
      The Protein Works (Whey Protein 360), Optimum Nutrition (Gold Standard 100% Whey),
      Healf (Sprout Living Epic Protein), Huel (Complete Protein), Bulk (Pure Whey
      Protein), and Naked Nutrition (Chocolate Whey Protein Powder). Fourteen opportunities
      were identified — thirteen sourced from competitor patterns, plus one latent opportunity
      derived from comparing flavour ranges across all six: Myprotein's 50+ flavours is the
      widest range in the category by a large margin, but the PDP makes almost no conversion
      use of it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── The Protein Works ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">The Protein Works</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">theproteinworks.com &mdash; Whey Protein 360 BLACK Innovation</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="In-page product tier comparison table"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Desktop"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="tpw-tier-comparison-table"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the main product content, TPW includes a "Worth the upgrade?" section presenting a
        structured side-by-side table comparing their three whey tiers (BLACK, GOLD, PLATINUM)
        across ~10 nutritional attributes: price per serving, protein per serving, protein sources,
        calories, vitamins &amp; minerals, approved health benefits, flavour count, digestive enzymes,
        and GLP-1 compatibility. Each column is framed with a purchase-intent label ("Best Price",
        "Best Value", "Best Rated") and uses check/cross marks for boolean attributes. Links from
        the table go directly to each tier's product page.
        <img src={imgTpwTierComparison.src} alt="TPW in-page product tier comparison table showing BLACK, GOLD and PLATINUM tiers side by side" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A user on an entry-level product page is often mid-decision — they know they want whey
        but haven't committed to a tier. Surfacing the upgrade comparison on the same page captures
        that indecision in favour of a higher-value product without requiring navigation elsewhere.
        The framing ("Best Price" vs "Best Value") doesn't make the entry tier feel inferior — it
        makes the middle tier feel obviously worth the small price increase. This is a well-established
        CRO pattern for increasing average order value.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein sells Impact Whey, Impact Whey Advanced, and THE Whey as a de facto tier stack
        but the PDP makes no attempt to surface this. A user on Impact Whey has no in-page prompt
        to consider Impact Whey Advanced without navigating away. A compact "Compare the range"
        module — even a 2-column card comparison — could intercept undecided shoppers. The labelling
        approach ("Best Value", "Most Popular") is worth borrowing directly.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Per-serving price on each size option"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="tpw-per-serving-price"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW's size selector displays the price-per-serving directly beneath each size chip:
        20 shakes (600g) at £0.55 each, 40 shakes at £0.50 each, 80 shakes at £0.43 each,
        160 shakes at £0.40 each. The cost-per-serving is always visible — no interaction required.
        <img src={imgTpwSizeSelector.src} alt="TPW size selector showing per-serving price beneath each size option" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A larger bag is a higher upfront price. Showing cost-per-serving reframes the decision:
        the larger purchase becomes cheaper per use, not just a bigger spend. This framing reduces
        the psychological friction of committing to a larger size and nudges users toward higher-value
        orders. It also eliminates the mental arithmetic a user would otherwise have to do themselves.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows the total price per size option but does not display price-per-serving on
        the size chips. Adding cost-per-serving beneath each size option on Impact Whey would make
        the value case for larger sizes immediately legible — particularly for a product sold in
        sizes ranging from 500g to 5kg, where the per-serve savings on larger bags are significant.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Rating distribution bars with percentage breakdown"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust"
      opportunityId="tpw-rating-breakdown-bars"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW's reviews section shows the full star-by-star percentage distribution alongside the
        aggregate score: 5★ 40%, 4★ 4%, 3★ 8%, 2★ 11%, 1★ 37%. Each tier has a proportional
        horizontal bar and explicit percentage. The distribution is shown unfiltered — even when
        the split is unflattering.
        <img src={imgTpwReviewsBreakdown.src} alt="TPW rating distribution showing percentage bars per star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Showing the full distribution is paradoxically a trust signal. Users who see only an
        aggregate score are left to wonder whether it reflects genuine spread. A visible distribution
        lets customers self-qualify — a user who reads 1-star reviews to understand failure modes
        is more informed and less likely to return. Hiding the distribution invites suspicion;
        showing it honestly reduces it.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows an aggregate rating and total count but no star-by-star breakdown on the PDP.
        With 210,000+ reviews, Myprotein has far more data to make this credible and useful. A
        distribution bar chart in the reviews section — showing the likely dominant 4- and 5-star
        clusters on Impact Whey — would add a transparency signal without undermining confidence.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Optimum Nutrition ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Optimum Nutrition</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">optimumnutrition.com &mdash; Gold Standard 100% Whey Protein Powder</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Review attribute highlights beside the star rating"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,conversion"
      opportunityId="on-review-attribute-highlights"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Directly below ON's star rating and review count, a short inline callout reads:
        <strong>"Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money."</strong>
        Each attribute is a clickable link that jumps to the reviews section filtered to reviews
        mentioning that dimension. The callout appears above the product bullets and the
        add-to-cart area — it is the first thing a user reads after the aggregate score.
        <img src={imgOnAtf.src} alt="Optimum Nutrition PDP showing 'Highly rated by customers for: Delivery Speed, Taste and Mixability, Value for Money' directly below the star rating" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A star rating tells a user how well-liked a product is. An attribute summary tells them
        <em>why</em>. For a shopper comparing two proteins with similar ratings, "Taste and Mixability"
        called out explicitly is a significantly stronger signal than "4.4 stars". It collapses
        the work of reading dozens of reviews into a three-word reassurance, and the clickable
        links give curious users a direct path to filtered evidence.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score and total count but does not break reviews
        down by attribute near the rating. With 210,000+ reviews on Impact Whey, the data to surface
        attribute-level highlights clearly exists. Even a static, editorially curated version —
        "Customers rate this highly for taste variety and value per serving" — near the star rating
        would provide this signal. A dynamic version powered by review tagging would be the stronger
        long-term implementation.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="AI-generated review summary with topic filter chips"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,content"
      opportunityId="on-ai-review-summary"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        At the top of ON's reviews section, before any individual review, an AI-synthesised paragraph
        summarises what customers say: <em>"Customers praise its great taste, easy mixing, and high
        value, making it a top choice for serious athletes."</em> Below the search and sort controls
        sits a row of topic filter chips — "size", "ingredients", "results", "absorption", "quality",
        "weight", "smell", "taste" — each filtering the review list to reviews mentioning that topic.
        <img src={imgOnReviews.src} alt="Optimum Nutrition reviews section showing AI summary paragraph and topic filter chips" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        No one reads 1,725 reviews. An AI synthesis gives users the substance of the community's
        verdict in ten seconds. For high-review-count products, the reviews section risks becoming
        noise rather than signal — the summary resolves this. The topic chips extend the utility:
        a user who cares specifically about mixability can filter directly rather than hunting through
        pages. Together they turn the reviews section from a scrollable wall of text into a
        structured, navigable knowledge base.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey has 210,000+ reviews — a dataset that makes ON's 1,725 look nascent.
        Yet the reviews section is a standard paginated list with star and sort filters only — no
        synthesis, no topic navigation, no AI summary. A product with this review volume is exactly
        where an AI summary would be most useful and most credible. Even a static editorial summary
        updated quarterly would be a meaningful step. Topic chips mapped to common themes — flavour,
        mixability, value, results — would be relatively low effort against an existing tagged
        review corpus.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Healf ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Healf</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">healf.com &mdash; Sprout Living Epic Protein (Vanilla Lucuma)</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Goal-based use-case chips above the add-to-cart"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="personalisation,conversion"
      opportunityId="healf-goal-chips"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Immediately below the product title and star rating, Healf asks: "What's your focus with
        [product name]?" and presents four selectable chips: "Muscle building", "Recovery",
        "Weight management", "Something else". Selecting a chip is paired with an "Assess
        suitability" entry point (a tab alongside "Product description") that helps users determine
        whether the product fits their specific goal. Both elements appear above the price and
        add-to-cart section.
        <img src={imgHealfSubscribe.src} alt="Healf PDP showing goal chips (Muscle building, Recovery, Weight management) and Assess suitability tab above the add-to-cart" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Protein powder is bought for different reasons by different people. A user targeting
        muscle building needs to know about protein-per-serving and amino acid profile; a recovery
        buyer cares about EAAs and digestibility. A goal chip doesn't just personalise the
        experience — it signals that the brand understands why the user is here, which reduces
        purchase hesitation. The suitability assessment adds a layer of confidence: the user
        is being actively helped to make the right decision rather than left to judge alone.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey PDP makes no attempt to qualify the user's goal or surface
        goal-specific content. For a product used across a wide range of goals — muscle gain,
        weight loss, general health, sports recovery — a simple goal chip selector could unlock
        context-relevant content: the relevant benefit bullets, a matched FAQ, or a
        "this product is a good fit for you" confirmation signal. Even a static version (chips
        that scroll to a relevant section) would add meaningful reassurance before the add-to-cart.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Subscribe & save as primary CTA with inline benefit callouts"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="healf-subscribe-primary-cta"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        On Healf's PDP, the subscription option is presented as the dominant choice — it is the
        first, darker button in the add-to-cart area, labelled "Subscribe &amp; save 10%", with
        the discounted price (£32.84) alongside the crossed-out full price (£41.99). Two inline
        benefit lines sit beneath it: "✓ Free delivery on subscriptions" and "✓ Free sample each
        month". A sticky bar persists at the bottom of the screen throughout the page scroll,
        showing the same subscription framing and price.
        <img src={imgHealfLower.src} alt="Healf sticky ATC bar showing Subscribe & save 10% as primary CTA with discounted price" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Defaulting to subscription — rather than treating it as an optional upgrade — changes
        the conversion dynamic. The user's path of least resistance is now the recurring order,
        not the one-time purchase. Showing the specific benefits inline (free delivery, free
        sample) makes the value exchange concrete at the moment of decision, rather than requiring
        the user to hunt for subscription terms. The sticky bar ensures this framing is always
        present regardless of where the user is on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein has a Subscribe &amp; Save option on PDPs but it is presented as a secondary
        choice alongside the standard one-time purchase. Inverting the hierarchy — making
        Subscribe the primary/pre-selected option and adding two or three specific benefit
        callouts inline ("Free delivery · Cancel anytime · Save X%") — would increase subscription
        conversion without requiring the user to seek out the option. This is a framing change
        rather than a feature build.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Huel ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Huel</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">uk.huel.com &mdash; Complete Protein</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Flavour selector as a visual list with photography and bestseller label"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="discovery,conversion"
      opportunityId="huel-flavour-selector"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Huel presents flavour options as a vertical list of cards rather than colour swatches.
        Each card shows a product lifestyle photograph, the flavour name, the price per bag
        (£22.50/bag), and a quantity add button. The most popular option is labelled
        <strong>🔥 BESTSELLER</strong> in the top-left of its card. Users can see all six flavours
        at once with no hover or tooltip required.
        <img src={imgHuelAtf.src} alt="Huel flavour selector showing visual cards with product photography, BESTSELLER label, price per bag, and add button" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Flavour is one of the most anxiety-inducing decisions in protein purchasing — especially
        for first-time buyers who have no reference point for what "Strawberries &amp; Cream" or
        "Banana Milkshake" will taste like. Photography gives sensory cues that a colour swatch
        cannot. The BESTSELLER label functions as social proof at the point of flavour selection,
        reducing decision paralysis by giving the user a safe default. Showing price per bag inline
        also means there are no surprises when the flavour choice affects pricing.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey flavour selector uses small circular swatches with flavour names
        on hover — functional but minimal. With 50+ flavours, a user has almost no visual cues
        to guide their choice. A redesigned selector that shows even a partial visual treatment —
        lifestyle imagery for the top 6–8 flavours, a "Best Seller" label on the most-purchased
        option, and inline popularity signals — would meaningfully reduce the cognitive load of
        an already complex choice and nudge undecided users toward the most-loved options.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Subscription delivery frequency selector in the add-to-cart"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="huel-subscription-frequency"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        In the add-to-cart panel, alongside the subscription price (£22.50, 10% off one-time),
        Huel presents a delivery frequency selector with four options: every 2, 4, 6, or 8 weeks.
        The selected frequency is displayed inline. One-time purchase remains available as a
        secondary option. Price per serving (£0.87 subscription / £0.96 one-time) is shown as a
        highlighted chip beside the serving count, above the price.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Subscription hesitation frequently comes down to commitment anxiety: "What if I don't go
        through a bag every month?" Offering frequency choice removes this objection at source.
        A user who trains three times a week will use protein differently from someone who uses it
        daily. Frequency flexibility also increases subscription retention — customers who chose
        their own interval are less likely to cancel because they have too much stock. The
        per-serving price chip reframes the subscription from "how much I'm spending" to
        "how much each shake costs", which is a more palatable number.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Subscribe &amp; Save is a binary choice — subscribe or don't — with a fixed
        delivery cadence. Introducing selectable frequency options (every 4, 6, or 8 weeks) in
        the ATC panel would remove the most common objection to subscribing for lower-frequency
        users. This is a framing and UX change rather than a logistics build, since flexible
        subscription intervals are standard in most subscription fulfilment platforms. Pairing
        it with a per-serving price chip displayed above the total price would reinforce the
        value case simultaneously.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Bulk ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Bulk</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">bulk.com &mdash; Pure Whey Protein™</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Pre-checked 'Customers also bought' bundle with running total and single add-all CTA"
      competitor="Bulk"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="bulk-fbt-bundle"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the main product panel, Bulk shows a "Customers also bought" section with three
        complementary products — each with a pre-ticked checkbox, product image, name, variant,
        star rating, and discounted price. Below the three items, a live running total shows the
        combined saving: <strong>"Total price £55.97 → £31.97"</strong>. A single full-width
        green CTA — "Add selection to basket" — adds all ticked items to the basket in one click.
        Users can untick any item to remove it and the total updates accordingly.
        <img src={imgBulkMid.src} alt="Bulk 'Customers also bought' section with pre-checked items, running total, and single add-all CTA" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Pre-ticking the bundle items shifts the default behaviour: the user must actively opt out
        of the additional products rather than opt in. Combined with the running total — which makes
        the bundled saving immediately legible — and a single CTA, this pattern significantly
        reduces the friction of multi-item purchases. A user buying whey protein is almost always
        also a candidate for creatine, a shaker, or a complementary supplement; surfacing those
        with one-click add removes the need for a second purchase journey.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's "Frequently bought with" section shows related products but functions as a
        standard carousel without checkboxes, a running total, or a bundle CTA. Introducing a
        pre-checked bundle mechanic — even for a curated set of two products (e.g. Impact Whey +
        Creatine Monohydrate) — with a combined discounted total and a single "Add both to basket"
        CTA would be a meaningful conversion lever, particularly for first-time buyers who are
        likely building out their first supplement stack.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Live Trustpilot feed with timestamped recent reviews on the PDP"
      competitor="Bulk"
      viewport="Desktop"
      categories="trust"
      opportunityId="bulk-live-trustpilot-feed"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the main product content, Bulk embeds a full Trustpilot widget showing the aggregate
        score ("Excellent, based on 65,071 reviews") alongside four individual review cards pulled
        in live from Trustpilot. Each card shows the reviewer's name, star rating, review title,
        truncated review text, a "Verified" badge, and a timestamp — "6 hours ago", "7 hours ago",
        "8 hours ago". The section notes "Showing our 4 &amp; 5 star reviews."
        <img src={imgBulkLower.src} alt="Bulk live Trustpilot feed showing four timestamped recent review cards embedded in the PDP" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        An aggregate score tells a user what others think; a live feed of recent timestamped reviews
        tells them that people are buying and reviewing right now. The recency signal — "6 hours ago"
        — is a form of demand proof that a static score cannot provide. Verified badges and named
        reviewers add authenticity. This pattern is particularly effective for new visitors arriving
        from paid ads (like the Bulk URL with UTM parameters) who have no prior brand familiarity
        and need trust established quickly.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score on the PDP but does not embed a live feed
        of recent individual reviews. Given Myprotein's review volume (210,000+), a live widget
        showing the most recent 3–4 reviews would be highly credible — there will always be a
        review from today or yesterday. This is a low-effort integration using the standard
        Trustpilot embed widget, and would make the trust signal on the PDP substantially more
        dynamic than a static score badge.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Naked Nutrition ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Naked Nutrition</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">nakednutrition.com &mdash; Chocolate Whey Protein Powder (2280g)</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="'% would recommend' metric displayed alongside the star rating"
      competitor="Naked Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust"
      opportunityId="naked-nutrition-recommend-pct"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        In the reviews section header, Naked Nutrition displays two parallel metrics at equal
        visual weight: the aggregate star rating ("4.8 ★ Based on 7,479 reviews") on the left,
        and "99% would recommend these products" on the right. The recommendation percentage
        sits at the same typographic scale as the rating — both are the first things a user
        reads when they reach the reviews section.
        <img src={imgNakedRecommend.src} alt="Naked Nutrition reviews section showing '4.8 stars based on 7,479 reviews' alongside '99% would recommend these products' at equal visual weight" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A star rating tells a user how well-liked a product is on a numeric scale. A
        recommendation percentage tells them something more human: would the people who bought
        this buy it again, or tell a friend? These are different questions with different
        psychological weight. A user who is undecided is often asking "will I regret this?" — and
        "99% of buyers would recommend it" answers that question more directly than "4.8 out of 5."
        The two metrics complement rather than duplicate each other.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein surfaces a Trustpilot aggregate score on the PDP but no recommendation
        percentage. With 210,000+ reviews on Impact Whey, Myprotein almost certainly has a
        high "would recommend" rate that would make this signal very credible. Adding a
        "X% of customers would recommend this product" line beside or below the aggregate
        score — ideally sourced from review platform data already collected — would add a
        distinct and emotionally resonant trust signal at minimal implementation cost.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Review cards that show which specific variant the reviewer purchased"
      competitor="Naked Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,discovery"
      opportunityId="naked-nutrition-review-variant-attr"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Each review card on Naked Nutrition shows a "Reviewing" block beneath the reviewer's
        name: a thumbnail of the specific product, the product name, and the exact variant
        purchased — e.g. "Vanilla Whey Protein Powder | Naked Vanilla Whey – 5LB". This appears
        as a distinct sub-card within the reviewer metadata column, before the review text.
        <img src={imgNakedReviewVariant.src} alt="Naked Nutrition review card showing 'Reviewing: Vanilla Whey Protein Powder | Naked Vanilla Whey – 5LB' with product thumbnail beneath the reviewer name" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A taste review is only meaningful if you know which flavour the reviewer bought. On a
        product with multiple variants, aggregating all reviews into a single undifferentiated
        list degrades the usefulness of every review: a "great flavour!" comment from someone
        who bought Vanilla is noise to a shopper deciding between Chocolate Brownie and Salted
        Caramel. Showing the purchased variant turns each review into a contextually relevant
        data point rather than a generic endorsement. It also subtly reinforces trust — it
        confirms the reviewer actually bought and received a specific product.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's Impact Whey reviews are aggregated across all 50+ flavours and multiple
        sizes with no variant attribution displayed. A user choosing between flavours has no
        way to filter or identify which reviews are relevant to their choice. Adding the
        purchased variant (flavour + size) as a metadata line on each review card — even as a
        small text label — would make the review corpus significantly more useful for
        flavour-undecided shoppers. This is particularly high-value given the latent flavour
        range opportunity already identified: if Myprotein surfaces 50+ flavours as a
        conversion argument, variant-attributed reviews become the evidence layer that makes
        that argument credible.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Latent Myprotein Opportunity ─────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Myprotein — latent opportunity</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">Derived from comparing flavour ranges across all five competitors</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Flavour range as an active conversion argument"
      competitor="Myprotein"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,trust,discovery"
      opportunityId="mp-flavour-range-conversion"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Myprotein offers 50+ flavours of Impact Whey — the widest range of any brand reviewed
        by a significant margin (Bulk: ~20, ON: ~15, Huel: 6, TPW: 5). This is a genuine
        product-level advantage. The current PDP treats flavour range as a functional selector
        only: users scroll through swatches to pick one. The range is not surfaced as a claim,
        a social proof signal, or a conversion argument anywhere on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Range communicates investment, confidence, and scale in a way that a single product spec
        cannot. A brand with 50 flavours has clearly iterated based on customer demand; a brand
        with 5 hasn't. For a first-time buyer choosing between Myprotein and a competitor,
        "50+ flavours" is a reassurance that they won't be stuck with one option if their first
        choice doesn't work out — it lowers the perceived risk of committing. Range also functions
        as a discovery driver: users who come for one flavour often browse others and return for
        a second purchase in a different variant. None of the five competitors reviewed can
        credibly make this claim.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Three concrete ways to activate this on the PDP:
        <br /><br />
        <strong>1. Surface the number as a claim.</strong> A line near the flavour selector —
        "Choose from 50+ flavours" — makes the range legible immediately, in the same way Huel
        says "Choose from 6 tasty flavours." The number itself is the signal.
        <br /><br />
        <strong>2. Add bestseller and new labels to the selector.</strong> With 50+ options,
        the selector currently creates choice paralysis. Labelling the top 3–5 as "Best Seller"
        and any new additions as "New" gives undecided users a socially validated shortcut —
        the same pattern Bulk uses for pricing and Huel uses for its top flavour. This turns
        range from a liability (too many choices) into an asset (community-validated defaults).
        <br /><br />
        <strong>3. Pair range with per-serving price in the product summary.</strong>
        A compact line above the ATC — "50+ flavours · from £0.54/serving" — creates a
        value-and-range statement that no competitor can match. It pre-empts the two most
        common objections (taste uncertainty and price) in a single line.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Where MP Leads ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Areas Where Myprotein Already Leads</h2>
    <p>
      Myprotein's review volume (210,000+ on Impact Whey alone) is a trust advantage none of
      these five competitors come close to matching — Bulk has 65,071 Trustpilot reviews
      (brand-level), ON has ~1,725 on this product, TPW has 135, Healf's product has 27, and Huel
      does not surface a review count on the PDP. Myprotein's flavour range (50+ for Impact Whey)
      far exceeds all five. The Trustpilot aggregate score is already surfaced on the Myprotein
      PDP. Myprotein's structured content tabs (nutrition, ingredients, key benefits, reviews)
      give users more ways to explore detail without navigating away than most competitor pages
      reviewed. Huel's brand storytelling depth (celebrity endorsements, press mentions) reflects
      a different marketing budget and positioning — not a PDP UX gap for Myprotein to close.
    </p>
  </section>

